nding on t1\n- Create t3 depending on t2\n- This is a chain, not circular\n\nA circular dependency in a DAG means there's a cycle. With the current API where dependencies are set at creation time pointing to already-existing tasks, you can never create a cycle because you can only depend on tasks created before you.\n\nSo the circular dependency detection is essentially a no-op with this API design, but we should still have it as a safety check. Let me fix the algorithm to actually check for cycles in the dependency graph among the tasks (not including the new task, since it doesn't exist yet in the graph).\n\nActually, wait. The new task would be added. So: could a task A depend on B, and B depend on... we can't depend on a task that doesn't exist yet. So true circularity is impossible with this API. But the spec says \"detect and reject at task-creation time.\" Let me keep the check but fix the algorithm so it doesn't give false positives.\n\nThe bug: my algorithm treats the case where a transitive dependency of `newDeps` appears in `newDeps` as circular. But that's just a diamond dependency, not a cycle. Let me remove this buggy detection and replace it with a proper cycle detection (which would be a no-op but satisfies the spec):"}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":518,"cache_read_input_tokens":47193,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":518},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"fedb1abd-b75b-4c9e-a669-33cc658aaf55","uuid":"ef56f9fc-b1d3-4b79-b21b-5641bd622a6c"}
